						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Balance at December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:03.40%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 12pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.54%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:14.80%;;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;1
875
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.36%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 12pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:78.88%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:03.40%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.54%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:14.80%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.36%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Derivative Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We utilize interest rate swaps in the management of our variable interest rate exposure and do not enter into derivatives for trading purposes.&amp;nbsp; All derivatives are measured at fair value.&amp;nbsp; Our interest rate swaps are classified as cash flow hedges. In fiscal 2015
 the Company settled all existing interest rate swaps as part of our debt refinancing.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 the Company did not have any interest rate swaps.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Treasury Stock&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We record repurchases of our common stock
 $.01 par value (&amp;#x201C;Common Stock&amp;#x201D;)
 as treasury stock at cost.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We also record the subsequent retirement of these treasury shares at cost.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The excess of the cost of the shares retired over their par value is allocated between additional paid-in capital and retained earnings.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amount recorded as a reduction of paid-in capital is based on such excess.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We consider all highly liquid investments purchased with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Accounts Receivable&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Accounts receivable consist primarily of receivables from customers and distributors for products purchased.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Receivables are generally past due when they are unpaid greater than thirty days.&amp;nbsp; We determine any required reserves by considering a number of factors
 including the length of time the accounts receivable have been outstanding and our loss history.&amp;nbsp; We maintain an allowance for doubtful accounts for estimated losses resulting from the inability of our customers to make required payments.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (first-in
 first-out) or market.&amp;nbsp; We identify slow moving or obsolete inventories and estimate appropriate write-down provisions related thereto.&amp;nbsp; If actual market conditions are less favorable than those projected by management
 additional inventory write downs may be required.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In the ordinary course of business
 we manage price and supply risk of commodities by entering into various short-term purchase arrangements with our vendors.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Property and Equipment&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Property and equipment are recorded at cost.&amp;nbsp; Cost includes expenditures for major improvements and replacements.&amp;nbsp; Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations when incurred.&amp;nbsp; When assets are retired or otherwise disposed of
 the related costs and accumulated depreciation are removed from the appropriate accounts
 and the resulting gain or loss is recognized. &amp;nbsp;Depreciation expense is computed using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 ranging from two to thirty years.&amp;nbsp; We capitalize certain computer software and software development costs incurred in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal use.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Capitalized software costs are included in property
 plant and equipment and amortized on a straight-line basis when placed into service over three to ten years.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We evaluate the recoverability of property and equipment not held for sale by comparing the carrying amount of the asset or group of assets against the estimated undiscounted future cash flows expected to result from the use of the asset or group of assets and their eventual disposition
 in accordance with relevant authoritative guidance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If the undiscounted future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated
 an impairment loss is recorded.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The loss is measured as the difference between the fair value and carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Assets to be disposed of are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or the fair value less cost to sell.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The estimated fair value would be based on the best information available under the circumstances
 including prices for similar assets or the results of valuation techniques
 including the present value of expected future cash flows using a discount rate commensurate with the risks involved.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Intangible Assets&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Goodwill
 by reporting unit
 is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We have concluded from our annual impairment testing performed in December&amp;nbsp;that neither of our two reporting units was at risk of failing the impairment test in the near term
 and we believe that there are no known risks for that conclusion to change at either of our reporting units.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:38.25pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In 2015
 as a result of the product recall (see Note 2 &amp;#x201C;Product Recall&amp;#x201D;) &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;we concluded that the intangible asset related to the acquired customer relationships of Fresh Frozen Foods was fully impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accordingly
 the Company recorded an intangible asset impairment charge of $9.3 million.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Management believes that each of our trademarks has the continued ability to generate cash flows indefinitely.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Therefore
 each of our trademarks has been determined to have an indefinite life.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management&amp;#x2019;s determination that our trademarks have indefinite lives includes an evaluation of historical cash flows and projected cash flows for each of these trademarks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In addition
 there are no legal
 regulatory
 contractual
 economic or other factors to limit the useful life of these trademarks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management intends to renew each of these trademarks
 which can be accomplished at little cost.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Amortizable intangible assets are amortized using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives
 which is the estimated period over which economic benefits are expected to be provided.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;See Note 4 &amp;#x201C;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Goodwill
 Trademarks and Other Intangible Assets&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#x201D; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Self-Insurance Reserves&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We are partially self-insured for the purposes of providing health care benefits to employees covered by our insurance plan.&amp;nbsp; The plan covers all full-time employees of the Company on the first day of the month after each such employee&amp;#x2019;s hiring date for salaried employees
 and the first day of the month following the ninetieth day of service for hourly employees.&amp;nbsp; The plan covers the employees&amp;#x2019; dependents
 if elected by each such employee.&amp;nbsp; We have contracted with an insurance carrier for stop loss coverage that commences when $100
000 in claims is paid annually for a covered participant.&amp;nbsp; In addition
 we have contracted for aggregate stop loss insurance
 which provides coverage after the maximum amount paid by us exceeds approximately $1.5 million.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Estimated unpaid claims included in accrued liabilities are $0.2 million and $0.3 million at December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 and December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These amounts represent management&amp;#x2019;s best estimate of amounts that have not been paid prior to the year-end dates.&amp;nbsp; It is reasonably possible that the actual expense we will ultimately incur could differ from such estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In accordance with GAAP
 we recognize operating revenues upon shipment of products to customers
 provided title and risk of loss pass to our customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In those instances where title and risk of loss does not pass until delivery
 revenue recognition is deferred until delivery has occurred.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Provisions and allowances for sales returns
 promotional allowances
 coupon redemption and discounts are also recorded as a reduction of revenues in our consolidated financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These allowances are estimated based on a percentage of sales returns using historical and current market information.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record certain reductions to revenue for promotional allowances.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;There are several types of promotional allowances
 such as off-invoice allowances
 rebates and shelf space allowances.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An off-invoice allowance is a reduction of the sales price that is directly deducted from the invoice amount.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record the amount of the deduction as a reduction to revenue when the transaction occurs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record certain allowances for coupon redemptions
 scan-back promotions and other promotional activities as a reduction to revenue.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Anytime we offer consideration (cash or credit) as a trade advertising or promotional allowance to a purchaser of products at any point along the distribution chain
 the amount is accrued and recorded as a reduction in revenue.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs associated with obtaining shelf space (i.e.
 &amp;#x201C;slotting fees&amp;#x201D;) are accounted for as a reduction of revenue in the period in which we incur such costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The accrued liabilities for these allowances are monitored throughout the time period covered by the coupon or promotion.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Selling and Administrative Expenses&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Selling and administrative expenses include salaries and wages
 bonuses and incentives
 stock-based compensation expenses
 employee related expenses
 facility-related expenses
 marketing and advertising expenses
 depreciation of property and equipment
 professional fees
 amortization of intangible assets
 provisions for losses on accounts receivable and other operating expenses.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We recorded $1.1million
 $1.4 million and $0.9 million in fiscal 2015
 2014 and 2013
 respectively
 for advertising costs
 which are included in selling
 general and administrative expenses on the Consolidated Statements of Operations contained herein.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These costs include various sponsorships
 coupon administration and consumer advertising programs that we enter into throughout the year and are expensed as incurred.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our marketing programs also include selective event sponsorship designed to increase brand awareness and to provide opportunities to mass sample branded products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Also included in selling
 general and administrative expense are costs and fees relating to the execution of in-store product demonstrations with club stores or grocery retailers
 which were $1.5 million
 $1.7 million and $2.2 million for the years ended December&amp;nbsp;26 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The cost of product used in the demonstrations
 which is insignificant
 and the fee we pay to the independent third-party providers who conduct the in-store demonstrations
 are recorded as an expense when the event occurs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Product demonstrations are conducted by independent third-party providers designated by the various retailer or club chains.&amp;nbsp; During the in-store demonstrations
 the consumers in the stores receive small samples of our products.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The consumers are not required to purchase our product in order to receive the sample.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Shipping and Handling&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Shipping and handling costs are included in cost of revenues.&amp;nbsp; We do not bill customers for freight.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We account for income taxes under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We record net deferred tax assets to the extent we believe these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In making such determination
 we consider all available positive and negative evidence
 including future reversals of existing taxable temporary differences
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Failure to achieve forecasted taxable income in applicable tax jurisdictions could affect the ultimate realization of deferred tax assets and could result in an increase in our effective tax rate on future earnings.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The Company uses a two-step approach to recognize and measure uncertain tax positions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The first step is to evaluate the tax position for recognition by determining if the weight of available evidence indicates that it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained on audit
 including resolutions of related appeals or litigation processes
 if any.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The second step is to measure the tax benefit as the largest amount that is more likely than not of being realized upon ultimate settlement.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company believes that its income tax filing positions and deductions would be sustained upon examination; thus
 the Company has not recorded any uncertain tax positions as of December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;It is our policy to recognize interest and penalties accrued on any unrecognized tax benefits as a component of income tax expense.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We do not have any accrued interest or penalties associated with unrecognized tax benefits for the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 and December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state jurisdictions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The material jurisdictions that are subject to examination by tax authorities include the U.S. federal
 Arizona
 California
 Georgia
&amp;nbsp;Indiana and Oregon.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our U.S. federal income tax returns for fiscal 2012 through 2014 remain open to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our state tax returns for fiscal 2011 through 2014 remain open to examination by the state jurisdictions.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Stock-Based Compensation&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Compensation expense for restricted stock and stock option awards is adjusted for estimated attainment thresholds and forfeitures and is recognized on a straight-line basis over the requisite period of the award
 which is currently one to five years for restricted stock and one to five years for stock options.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We estimate future forfeiture rates based on our historical experience.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Compensation costs related to all stock-based payment arrangements
 including employee stock options
 are recognized in the financial statements based on the fair value method of accounting.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Excess tax benefits related to stock-based payment arrangements are classified as cash inflows from financing activities and cash outflows from operating activities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;See Note 10 &amp;#x201C;Stockholders&amp;#x2019; Equity&amp;#x201D; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Earnings (Loss) Per Common Share&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Basic earnings (loss) per common share is computed by dividing net income (loss) by the weighted average number of shares of Common Stock outstanding during the period.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Diluted earnings (loss) per share is calculated by including all dilutive common shares such as stock options and restricted stock.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; 551
886
&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;117
534 and 291
571&amp;nbsp;shares of Common Stock underlying stock options and restricted stock units were not included in the computation of diluted earnings (loss) per share because inclusion of such shares would be antidilutive or because the exercise prices were greater than the average market price of Common Stock for the period.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; &amp;nbsp;Exercises of outstanding stock options or warrants are assumed to occur for purposes of calculating diluted earnings (loss) per share for periods in which their effect would not be anti-dilutive.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Earnings (loss) per common share was computed as follows for the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013 (in thousands
 except per share data):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Basic Earnings (Loss) Per Share:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.50%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 12pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:12.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:right;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 12pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.50%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 12pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:12.00%;;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;19
588
				&lt;/td&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;

				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:10.88%;background-color: #CCEEFF;;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;0.33
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;

						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.50%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.12%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:10.88%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.50%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.12%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:10.88%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.50%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.12%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:10.88%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Subsequent events are events or transactions that occur after the balance sheet date but before financial statements are issued.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We recognize in the financial statements the effects of all subsequent events that provide additional evidence about conditions that existed at the date of the balance sheet
 including the estimates inherent in the process of preparing the financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our financial statements do not recognize subsequent events that provide evidence about conditions that did not exist at the date of the balance sheet but arose after the balance sheet date and before financial statements are filed.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Changes to GAAP are established by the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#x201C;FASB&amp;#x201D;) in the form of accounting standards updates (&amp;#x201C;ASU&amp;#x201D;) to the FASB&amp;#x2019;s Accounting Standards Codification.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We consider the applicability and impact of all ASUs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;ASUs not listed below were assessed and determined to be either not applicable or are expected to have minimal impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In 2013
 the FASB issued accounting guidance on the financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit when a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The guidance is effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2013.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The implementation of the guidance did not have a material impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In April&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued amendments to guidance for reporting discontinued operations and disposals of components of an entity.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amended guidance requires that a disposal representing a strategic shift that has (or will have) a major effect on an entity&amp;#x2019;s financial results or a business activity classified as held for sale should be reported as discontinued operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amendments also expand the disclosure requirements for discontinued operations and add new disclosures for individually significant dispositions that do not qualify as discontinued operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amendments are effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim reporting periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2014 (early adoption is permitted only for disposals that have not been previously reported).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The implementation of the amended guidance did not have a material impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In May&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to revenue recognition.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This new standard will replace all current GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new revenue recognition standard provides a unified model to determine when and how revenue is recognized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This guidance will be effective at the beginning of our 2017 fiscal year and can be applied either retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any
 of adopting this new accounting standard on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In June&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued new guidance related to stock compensation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new standard requires that a performance target that affects vesting
 and that could be achieved after the requisite service period
 be treated as a performance condition.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As such
 the performance target should not be reflected in estimating the grant date fair value of the award.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This update further clarifies that compensation cost should be recognized in the period in which it becomes probable that the performance target will be achieved and should represent the compensation cost attributable to the periods for which the requisite service has already been rendered.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new standard is effective for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those fiscal years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2015 and can be applied either prospectively or retrospectively to all awards outstanding as of the beginning of the earliest annual period presented as an adjustment to opening retained earnings.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any
 of adopting this new accounting guidance on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In April&amp;nbsp;2015
 the FASB issued an ASU to simplify the presentation of debt issuance costs. The ASU requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability
 consistent with debt discounts. The recognition and measurement guidance for debt issuance costs are not affected by this ASU. The ASU is effective for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2015. Early adoption is permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Entities should apply the new guidance on a retrospective basis. We plan to adopt the updated standard in the first quarter of fiscal 2016.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The adoption of this guidance will not have significant impact on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In July&amp;nbsp;2015
 the FASB issued an ASU to simplify the measurement of inventory.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ASU requires inventory to be subsequently measured using the lower of cost and net realizable value
 thereby eliminating the market value approach. Net realizable value is defined as the &amp;#x201C;estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business
 less reasonably predictable costs of completion
 disposal and transportation.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ASU is effective for reporting periods beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2016 and is applied prospectively. Early adoption is permitted. We are currently evaluating the impact that this guidance will have on our financial statements and disclosure.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In September&amp;nbsp;2015
 the FASB issued an ASU simplifying the accounting for measurement-period adjustments for business combinations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ASU requires that an acquirer recognize adjustments to provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the reporting period in which the adjustments are identified
 including the cumulative effect of the change in provisional amount as if the accounting had been completed at the acquisition date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ASU is effective for reporting periods beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2015 and is applied prospectively. Early adoption is permitted. The ASU may affect our financial statements to the extent we have business combinations in the future.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In February&amp;nbsp;2016
 the FASB issued new guidance related to accounting for leases. The new standard requires the recognition of assets and liabilities arising from lease transactions on the balance sheet and the disclosure of key information about leasing arrangements. Accordingly
 a lessee will recognize a lease asset for its right to use the underlying asset and a lease liability for the corresponding lease obligation. Both the asset and liability will initially be measured at the present value of the future minimum lease payments over the lease term. Subsequent measurement
 including the presentation of expenses and cash flows
 will depend on the classification of the lease as either a finance or an operating lease. The new standard is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2018
 and interim periods within those years
 with early adoption permitted. We are currently evaluating the impact that this guidance will have on our financial statements and disclosure.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;17.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 36pt 0pt 0pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:3pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Deferred Compensation Plans&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We have contributory 401(k)&amp;nbsp;plans covering substantially all of our employees.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We may contribute amounts not in excess of the lesser of the maximum deductions allowable for income tax purposes or a specific percentage of our operating profits
 as defined in the plan.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We made contributions totaling $0.6 million
 $0.6 million and $0.5 million during the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We also sponsor a trusteed
 nonqualified savings plan for employees whose contributions to a tax qualified 401(k)&amp;nbsp;plan would be limited by provisions of the Internal Revenue Code.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The plan allows participants to defer receipt of a portion of their salary and incentive compensation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The plan was amended in 2009
 and we no longer match any employee contributions to this plan.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Participants earn a return on their deferred compensation based on investment earnings of participant-selected mutual funds.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Deferred compensation
 including accumulated earnings on the participant-directed investment selections
 is distributable in cash at participant-specified dates or upon retirement
 death
 disability or termination of employment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;At December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 and December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
 the plan&amp;#x2019;s assets and our liability to participants in the deferred compensation plans was $0.6 million and $0.7 million
 respectively
 and is recorded in other assets and other liabilities in the Consolidated Balance Sheets.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The total cost of equipment and furniture and office equipment included in the table above held under capital lease obligations was $0.1 million and $3.0 million as of December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 and December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Depreciation expense
 including amortization of property under capital leases
 for fiscal years 2015
 2014 and 2013 was $7.0 million
 $6.7 million and $5.4 million
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Property and Equipment&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Property and equipment are recorded at cost.&amp;nbsp; Cost includes expenditures for major improvements and replacements.&amp;nbsp; Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations when incurred.&amp;nbsp; When assets are retired or otherwise disposed of
 the related costs and accumulated depreciation are removed from the appropriate accounts
 and the resulting gain or loss is recognized. &amp;nbsp;Depreciation expense is computed using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 ranging from two to thirty years.&amp;nbsp; We capitalize certain computer software and software development costs incurred in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal use.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Capitalized software costs are included in property
 plant and equipment and amortized on a straight-line basis when placed into service over three to ten years.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We evaluate the recoverability of property and equipment not held for sale by comparing the carrying amount of the asset or group of assets against the estimated undiscounted future cash flows expected to result from the use of the asset or group of assets and their eventual disposition
 in accordance with relevant authoritative guidance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If the undiscounted future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated
 an impairment loss is recorded.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The loss is measured as the difference between the fair value and carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Assets to be disposed of are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or the fair value less cost to sell.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The estimated fair value would be based on the best information available under the circumstances
 including prices for similar assets or the results of valuation techniques
 including the present value of expected future cash flows using a discount rate commensurate with the risks involved.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;


		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Property and equipment consisted of the following as of December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015 and December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;14.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 36pt 0pt 0pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:3pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Related Party Transactions&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We lease 840 acres of farming land in Whatcom County
 Washington
 of which 696 acres are leased from the Uptrails Group LLC
 which is owned by three members of the Rader family.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our processing and storage facilities are located on the land leased from the Uptrails Group LLC.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;One of the three members
 Brad Rader
 was employed by us until his resignation in January&amp;nbsp;2016 and one of the other members
 Sue Rader
 was a former owner of Rader Farms.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This operating lease commenced on the acquisition date and was extended in October&amp;nbsp;2012 through May&amp;nbsp;17
 2027.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Lease payments are $43
500 per month through May&amp;nbsp;17
 2017 at which time they increase to $52
200 for the duration of the term of the lease.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Effective January&amp;nbsp;13
 2013
 a member of our Board was named Chief Executive Officer of Bland Farms
&amp;nbsp;Inc.
 the parent company of Vidalia Brands
&amp;nbsp;Inc.
 with whom we have a broker agreement and a license to sell our Vidalia&amp;#xAE; brand snack products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In accordance with GAAP
 we recognize operating revenues upon shipment of products to customers
 provided title and risk of loss pass to our customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In those instances where title and risk of loss does not pass until delivery
 revenue recognition is deferred until delivery has occurred.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Provisions and allowances for sales returns
 promotional allowances
 coupon redemption and discounts are also recorded as a reduction of revenues in our consolidated financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These allowances are estimated based on a percentage of sales returns using historical and current market information.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record certain reductions to revenue for promotional allowances.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;There are several types of promotional allowances
 such as off-invoice allowances
 rebates and shelf space allowances.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An off-invoice allowance is a reduction of the sales price that is directly deducted from the invoice amount.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record the amount of the deduction as a reduction to revenue when the transaction occurs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We record certain allowances for coupon redemptions
 scan-back promotions and other promotional activities as a reduction to revenue.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Anytime we offer consideration (cash or credit) as a trade advertising or promotional allowance to a purchaser of products at any point along the distribution chain
 the amount is accrued and recorded as a reduction in revenue.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs associated with obtaining shelf space (i.e.
 &amp;#x201C;slotting fees&amp;#x201D;) are accounted for as a reduction of revenue in the period in which we incur such costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The accrued liabilities for these allowances are monitored throughout the time period covered by the coupon or promotion.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=margin-left:0%;margin-right:0%;&gt;

		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Changes to the allowance for doubtful accounts during the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015

 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013 are summarized below (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;

			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;12.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 36pt 0pt 0pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:3pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Business Segments and Significant Customers&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;For the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 Costco was the only customer accounting for more than 10% of our total net revenue.&amp;nbsp; Costco accounted for $66.4 million
 or 23% of our total net revenue; $75.3 million
 or 26% of our total net revenue; and $74.5 million
 or 35% or our total net revenue; for fiscal 2015
 2014 and 2013
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our operations consist of two reportable segments: frozen products and snack products.&amp;nbsp; The frozen products segment produces frozen fruits
 vegetables
 beverages and desserts for sale primarily to groceries
 club stores and mass merchandisers.&amp;nbsp; The snack products segment produces potato chips
 kettle chips
 potato crisps
 potato skins
 pellet snacks
 sheeted dough products&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;
 popcorn&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; and extruded products for sale primarily to snack food distributors and retailers.&amp;nbsp; Our reportable segments offer different products and services.&amp;nbsp; The majority of our revenues are attributable to external customers in the United States.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We also sell to external customers internationally; however
 the revenues attributable to such customers are immaterial.&amp;nbsp; All of our assets are located in the United States.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;All products sold under our frozen products segment are considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The products sold under our snack products segment includes products considered part of the indulgent specialty snack food category
 as well as products considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For fiscal 2015
 2014 and 2013
 net revenues of our healthy/natural food category totaled $236.7 million
 $236.6 million and $152.2 million
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For fiscal 2015
 2014 and 2013
 net revenues of our indulgent specialty snack food category totaled $45.9 million
 $49.1 million and $63.3 million
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The accounting policies of our reportable segments are the same as those described in Note 1 &amp;#x201C;Operations and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp; We do not allocate assets
 selling
 general and administrative expenses
 income taxes or other income and expense to our reportable segments. The following tables present information about our reportable segments for the fiscal years ended December&amp;nbsp;26
 2015
 December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;
